1---General-Zettels/Removing-Exceptional.content:
Suppose X_0 has finite measure, and we have to prove an inequality of the form
\| f \|_{L^p(X_0)} \lesssim C. \tag{1}
Equation (1) is almost equivalent to proving that for any subset X of X_0, there exists E \subset X with |E \cap X| \leq 1/2 so that
\| f \|_{L^p(X - E)} \lesssim C |X|^{1/p&#039;}. \tag{2}
Certainly (1) implies (2) by Hölder’s inequality. Conversely, if (2) holds, then we may find E_1 so that if X_1 = X - E_1, then
\| f \|_{L^p(X_1)} \lesssim C |X|^{1/p&#039;}. \tag{3}
Iterating, for each n \geq 1, we can apply (2) with X = X_n to find E_n \subset X_n so that if X_{n+1} = X_n - E_n,
\| f \|_{L^p(X_{n+1})} \lesssim C |X_n|^{1/p} \lesssim 2^{-n/p} C |X|^{1/p&#039;}. \tag{4}
Applying the triangle inequality, since X - \bigcup X_n is measure zero, we find
\| f \|_{L^p(X)} \leq \sum\nolimits_n \| f \|_{L^p(X_n)} \lesssim \sum 2^{-n/p} C |X|^{1/p&#039;} \lesssim C |X|^{1/p&#039;}. \tag{5}

